Database migrations (Flask-Migrate / Alembic).

## Common commands

    flask db upgrade            # apply pending migrations (use this on fresh installs and after pulling new revisions)
    flask db migrate -m "msg"   # autogenerate a new revision from model changes
    flask db downgrade          # roll back one revision
    flask db current            # show current revision
    flask db history            # show revision history

`FLASK_APP=run.py` and `DATABASE_URL` must be set in the environment.

## First-time prod baselining

Before this directory existed, the production database was created via
`db.create_all()` from create_db.py. To bring an existing prod database
under migration control, run ONCE:

    flask db stamp head

This records the current schema version without altering tables. After this,
all future schema changes go through `flask db migrate` + `flask db upgrade`.

## Authoring new migrations

1. Edit models.py.
2. Run `flask db migrate -m "describe the change"` against a postgres DB
   (a fresh local one is fine — alembic compares models to the live schema
   to generate the diff).
3. Open the generated file in migrations/versions/ and review it. Autogenerate
   often misses things (column type changes, server defaults, indexes on JSON
   keys) — fix manually before committing.
4. Run `flask db upgrade` locally to apply, run the test suite, and commit
   the migration alongside the model change.

## Notes

- The conftest.py test fixture uses `db.create_all()`, not migrations, so
  tests do not exercise the migration files. After non-trivial migrations,
  also test by running `flask db upgrade` against a fresh local database.
- Single-database configuration (no multi-bind support).
